<DOC><DOCNO> AP900309-0089 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-03-09-90 1222EST</FILEID><FIRST>d a AM-BRF--InjuryAward     03-09 0160</FIRST><SECOND>AM-BRF--Injury Award,0163</SECOND><HEAD>Woman Who Lost Senses of Sight, Smell and Taste Awarded $3.7Million</HEAD><DATELINE>POMONA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   A woman who claimed she was blinded andlost her senses of taste and smell because of injuries sufferedwhen a truck ran her off a freeway has been awarded $3.7 million.   ``Under the circumstances, we thought the award appropriate,''said Arthur Tiddle, foreman of the Pomona Superior Court jury thathanded down the judgment Tuesday.   Elaine Fleishman, a 61-year-old mother of five who used to be apart-time nanny, now attends the Braille Institute in RanchoMirage, her attorney, Amy C. Fisch, said Thursday.   The jurors found negligence on the part of the truck driver,Robert G. Meyer, 66, his employer, Road West Express, and thecompany that held the trucking permits, Roadex Inc.   An off-duty police officer testified he saw the truck move rightand strike a pickup, then swerve to the left and strike Ms.Fleishman's car.</TEXT></DOC>